ambridge): of Norman origin, possibly a metathesised variant of   Walrond   (see   Waldron  )."]},{"name":"Waldron","meanings":["English and Irish (Mayo): from the Norman personal name <i>Waleran</i>, <i>Galeran</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Walahram</i>, Old French <i>Galeran(t)</i>), composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner’ + <i>hrafn</i> ‘raven’. Compare   Walraven  . In Ireland, where it is common, this name was Gaelicized early as <b>Mac Bhalronta</b>, also later as <b>Mac Bhaildrin</b> and <b>de Bhaldraithe</b>.","English: habitational name from a place in Sussex named Waldron. The placename derives from Old English <i>wald</i> ‘woodland’ + <i>ærn</i> ‘building’.","History: This is the name of a prominent NH family, established there since the 17th century. Richard Walderne (born <i>c.</i> 1615) came to New England from Alchester, Warwickshire, England, <i>c.</i> 1640 and settled at Dover, NH."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Walrond was born in 1193, in Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom as the son of Richard de Bradfelle. He married Mrs. Richard Walrond in 1217, in Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1193–":"1193–Surnud","1193–Male":"1193–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1217":"1217","1200":"1200","Bef 1220":"enne 1220","1220":"1220","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","1193":"1193","Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Bradfield, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradfield, Devonshire, England":"Bradfield, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradfield, Devon, Eng":"Bradfield, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1193–":"1193–Kuollut","1193–Male":"1193–Kuollut","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1217":"1217","1200":"1200","Bef 1220":"ennen vuotta 1220","1220":"1220","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","1193":"1193","Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Bradfield, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bradfield, Devonshire, England":"Bradfield, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bradfield, Devon, Eng":"Bradfield, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1193–":"1193–Décédé","1193–Male":"1193–Décédé","1195–Female":"1195–Décédée","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1220–Male":"1220–Décédé","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1217":"1217","1200":"1200","Bef 1220":"avan